salmon <- read_csv('salmon_imports.csv')
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   year = col_integer(),
##   salmon_fresh = col_double()
## )

Make an exploratory scatter plot

salmon_scatter <- salmon %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = salmon_fresh))+
  geom_point()

salmon_scatter

#Overall it looks linear but with some variation. Concernsa re the few spikes

Linear regression:

-perform linear regression -call the model name -write out the model equation including actual variables and coefficients -think about the model

# format for linear regression is 
# model_name <- lm(y_variable ~ x_variable, data - df_name)

salmon_model <- lm(salmon_fresh ~ year, data = salmon)
salmon_model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = salmon_fresh ~ year, data = salmon)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)         year  
##   -14982940         7550
# imports(tons) = -14982940 + 7550 (year)

What does the slope mean?

The slope tells us how much slamon imports increase by each year ####What does the y -intercept mean. Why is it concerning? What does this mean about extrapolating this model for past values? The y - intercept means that at year = 0 there is a negative salmon import. This does not make sense. For extrapolating for past values a limit on how fat back needs to be set so the model makes sense.

Model Diagnostics

-use plot(model_name) to view model diagnostics -do residuals appear normally distirbuted -any concerns about heteroscedasticity or outliers

par(mfrow = c(2,2)) #use to view all graphs from plot at once
plot(salmon_model)

#residauls appear noramlly distrubuted
# some concerns about heteroscedasticitity
#maybe a few outliers

Explore fit and model signigicance

-does year significantly predict salmon imports -what does the R2 value mean in words -what proportion of the variance in salmon imports is NOT explained by year

summary(salmon_model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = salmon_fresh ~ year, data = salmon)
## 
## Residuals:
##    Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
## -49619  -6284   2722   9063  17884 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -1.498e+07  6.963e+05  -21.52   <2e-16 ***
## year         7.550e+03  3.475e+02   21.72   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 14860 on 26 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9478, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9458 
## F-statistic: 471.9 on 1 and 26 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
#p < .001

Year significantly predicts salmon imports The R2 value means that 94.6% of the variance in salmon imports can be predicted by the year. 5.4% is not explained by year

Prepare a final graph

salmon_final_graph <- salmon %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = salmon_fresh))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = TRUE, size = 0.5, color = "gray20") + #plots the linear model with a confidence interval (se)
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "U.S. Annual Fresh Salmon Imports\n(1,000 pounds)", title = "Salmon Imports Model") +
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0,0), limits = c(1990, 2017))

salmon_final_graph

Make predictions using the model

Lets say we want to make predictions for the years 2022, 2024, 2026, and 2028

new_years <- data.frame(year = c(2022, 2024, 2026, 2028)) #creates a new data frame with thte years we want to predict using our model

#now feed this new data frame into the predict() function 

future_predict <- predict(salmon_model, newdata = new_years, interval = "confidence")

future_predict
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 282298.5 267877.4 296719.6
## 2 297397.6 281656.7 313138.5
## 3 312496.8 295418.5 329575.0
## 4 327595.9 309166.6 346025.2
predictions <- data.frame(new_years, future_predict)

predictions  #a new data frame that binds the predictions to the years
##   year      fit      lwr      upr
## 1 2022 282298.5 267877.4 296719.6
## 2 2024 297397.6 281656.7 313138.5
## 3 2026 312496.8 295418.5 329575.0
## 4 2028 327595.9 309166.6 346025.2

Find Pearsons r (correlation)

salmon_cor <- cor.test(salmon$year, salmon$salmon_fresh)

salmon_cor
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  salmon$year and salmon$salmon_fresh
## t = 21.723, df = 26, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9429434 0.9878307
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9735387
#r=.974...strong positve correlation

Concluding Statement

Year significantly predicts salmon imports (b = 7.550e+03, t(26) = 21.72, p < 0.001) with a strong postive correlation between the two (Pearsons r = 0.974). The overall model (imports(tons) = -14982940 + 7550 (year)) explains a significant amoint of variacne in imports (F(1,26) = 472, p < 0.001, R2 = 0.95).
